<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-492-662  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 492 662.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computing Canada  July 20 1989 v15 n15 p36(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The municipal market. (geographic information systems) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Forrest, David.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Cities throughout the world are increasingly turning to geographicinformation systems (GIS) technology.andP;  Over the next ten years,municipalities will become one of the largest GIS markets.andP;  Citydepartments commonly use digital street network files and othergeographic information products developed by the US Census Bureauand Statistic Canada.andP;  About 75 to 80 percent of municipalinformation is geographically based.andP;  Cities such as Toronto,Burnaby and Edmonton have implemented integrated corporate systemswhich address the needs of all city departments.andP;  GISimplementations involving multiple departments are complex andtime-consuming tasks, but cities can only benefit from thecorporate perspective.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Geographic Information SystemsMunicipal GovernmentCitiesComputer Systems Integration.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>